<font color="#FF0000">A THANKFUL PARTICIPANT</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep  6  9:37:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
ED,<br><br>
Your post is more to the point than you can imagine.  I enjoyed the interchange because it is a rare opportunity for me to share such feelings.  A sort of play in words with a common spirit.  I am more of a dead serious type than most can imagine.  The intense side is the normal for me.  A friend that asked me to visit this site understood that, and in a way knew I would grow from the involvement.  The benefit I didn't expect was the ability to see members of this site as friends.  Some have become very special to me.<br><br>
The last several posts have narrowed in on the reasons why I have found comfort at this site.  Although I have a problem that I am just now defining I never saw it as a problem or war related.  Surprise!<br><br>
Ed<br><br>
Your comment about me being &quot;anhedonic&quot;.  Observant.  It is not the fact that I can't enjoy pleasure, I avoid it.  I live my life in the AAAA type style.  If things are extremely stressful I take on a heavier work load to ensure I have intensity.  It helps to keep the mind from drifting to those memories you avoid.  I manage six functions at my company to maintain the intensity and maintain a complete home office to ensure I use the whole day.  This intensity got me a free ride in an ambulance from work a few months ago.  3 hours later I was back in the office.  I know there is something wrong with that behavior, but it works for me.  The intensity of the special ops flying even as a civilian was a release.  Hung that up in November 94.  Miss it.<br><br>
I guess I like pain or at least severe intensity.  Ride a bike(pedal type) for miles in the hills.  Push to the pain limit and maintain it for hours.  It is a necessity to so involve the brain that all other thoughts are purged.  Everything I do, I do the same way.  Even running.  I could never walk or smell the roses.  I even garden the same way.  Your intuition is spot on.<br><br>
I admire Ed and Cook a great deal.  Honesty in their approach.  What you see is what you got.  I have formed a bond.  Chet has touched something also.  He understands, you all do.  I only hope that the therapeutic interchange has not effected your relationship with Ed.  I accept the responsibility.  I needed it and for some reason I thought he did.  Doc Spatz was wearing him down.<br><br>
There is another me as is there for all of us.  A much more serious side.  The rest of the world knows me as strong, able to carry any load.  A man who takes risks and lifts there responsibility by making decisions, influencing many millions of dollars and lives.  No one except this site knows my pain.  As such I still  don't want them to know.<br><br>
I don't propose that I suffer as some surely do.  I now know I am at risk and feel fortunate to have found you, my friends, at this juncture in my life.<br><br>
THANKS<br>

<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


